{{DEFAULTSORT:Easa, Ahmed}} [[Category:Living people]] [[Category:People from Malé]] [[Category:21st-century Maldivian male actors]] [[Category:Maldivian male film actors]] [[Category:1985 births]]

{{Infobox person | name = Ahmed Easa | image = Ahmed Easa.jpg | imagesize = | alt = Easa looking away from camera | caption = Easa at Baiskoafu launching event, 2018 | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|10|7}} | birth_place = [[Maakurathu (Raa Atoll)|R. Maakurathu]], Maldives | alma_mater = | occupation = Actor | yearsactive = 2011–present | spouse = | children = | works = | awards = }} '''Ahmed Easa''' (born 7 October 1985) is a Maldivian film actor.
==Career== In his childhood, Ahmed Easa watched [[Bollywood]] films and imitated the acting of [[Sunil Shetty]] in stage performances.<ref name=IntroAanandu>{{cite news |url=https://www.muniavas.com/4049 |title=Aanadu donning a different role in Dhevansoora |language=Divehi |work=Muniavas |last=Rasheed |first=Ahmed |date=27 January 2018 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20190406121340/https://www.muniavas.com/4049 |deadurl=no |archivedate=6 April 2019 |accessdate=6 April 2019 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> While watching his movies, Easa grew a fondness towards cinema and decided to pursue a career in acting "if granted with a chance worth holding for".<ref name=IntroAanandu/> He was first offered a role in [[Amjad Ibrahim]]'s romantic horror film ''[[Udhabaani]]'' (2009) but he rejected it since he was "too shy to be in front of the camera with his current physique".<ref name=IntroAanandu/> However, he made his film debut two years later with Hamid Ali's ''[[Laelaa]]'' (2011) co-starring [[Yoosuf Shafeeu]], [[Amira Ismail]] and Ali.<ref name=IntroAanandu/><ref name=Laelaa>{{cite news |url=http://www.haveeru.com.mv:80/dhivehi/entertainment/maldives_film_industry/111087 |title="Laela": Why is a good screenplay needed? |language=Divehi|work=Haveeru |last=Nadheem |first=Ahmed |date=6 October 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111011190147/http://www.haveeru.com.mv/dhivehi/entertainment/maldives_film_industry/111087 |deadurl=yes |archivedate=2011-10-11 |accessdate=5 October 2018 |df= }}</ref> The film revolves around two daughters who are forced into an arranged marriages by their parents.<ref name=Laelaa/> The film and his performance received a negative response from critics; "The newcomer is strictly average in his performance but he needs to be more confident in his moves and work on the dialogue delivery if needs to survive in the industry".<ref name=Laelaa/> The film was declared a flop at box office.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.haveeru.com.mv:80/dhivehi/entertainment/110747 |title=Laela's premiere: A big satisfaction for Hamid |language=Divehi|work=Haveeru |last=Nadheem |first=Ahmed |date=29 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002195434/http://www.haveeru.com.mv/dhivehi/entertainment/110747 |deadurl=yes |archivedate=2011-10-02 |accessdate=11 October 2018 |df= }}</ref>
After shooting a video single with [[Yoosuf Shafeeu]], Easa was asked to feature in his thirtieth direction ''[[Dhevansoora]]'' (2018), a [[Thriller film|suspense thriller film]] featuring an [[ensemble cast]] including Shafeeu, Mariyam Shifa, [[Ali Azim]] and [[Fathimath Azifa]] in pivotal roles.<ref name=mihaaruintro>{{cite news|url=https://mihaaru.com/entertainment/25449 |title="Dhevansoora": A suspense thriller by Eupe |language=Divehi|work=Mihaaru |last=Adhushan |first=Ahmed |date=21 October 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180328111609/https://mihaaru.com/entertainment/25449|deadurl=no |archivedate=28 March 2018 |accessdate=28 March 2018 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://mihaaru.com/entertainment/27223 |title="Dhevansoora" to release on February 6 |language=Divehi|work=Mihaaru |last=Adhushan |first=Ahmed |date=29 November 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180328111057/https://mihaaru.com/entertainment/27223|deadurl=no |archivedate=28 March 2018 |accessdate=28 March 2018 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> He initially shot for the role of a policeman, portrayed by [[Mohamed Faisal (actor)|Mohamed Faisal]] in the film, before Shafeeu suggested he switch to a "more complex" role since he was unable to find anyone "who fits the bill" for that role.<ref name=IntroAanandu/> Revolving around a murder investigating, Easa played a delivery boy who has been accused to be involved in the murder crime.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sun.mv/96653 |title=Dhevansoora is a must watch |language=Divehi |work=Sun |last=Fareeha |first=Aishath |date=4 November 2017 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20181120063343/https://sun.mv/96464 |deadurl=no |archivedate=20 November 2018 |accessdate=20 November 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The film received positive reviews from critics and was considered a "norm-breaker" for the Maldivian cinema.<ref name=Dhevansoora/> Ahmed Hameed Adam reviewing from VNews applauded Easa's performance while playing the "strong-headed man and the vulnerable attacker".<ref name=Dhevansoora>{{cite news |url=http://vnews.mv/95298 |title=Dhevansoora: Re-writing History of Maldivian Cinema |language=Divehi |work=VNews |last=Adam |first=Ahmed Hameed |date=8 February 2018 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20190419092414/http://vnews.mv/95298 |deadurl=no |archivedate=19 April 2019 |accessdate=19 April 2019 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He then starred in the first Maldivian web-series, a romantic drama by [[Fathimath Nahula]], ''[[Huvaa]]''.<ref name=Huvaa>{{cite news|url=https://mihaaru.com/entertainment/31773 |title=Huvaa: Nahula starts her web-series |work=Mihaaru |language=Divehi |last=Adhushan |first=Ahmed |date=27 February 2018 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/uoRc8 |deadurl=no |archivedate=30 November 2018 |accessdate=30 November 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The series consisting of sixty episodes and streamed through the digital platform Baiskoafu, centers around a happy and radiant family which breaks into despairing pieces after a tragic incident that led to an unaccountable loss.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sun.mv/110406 |title="Huvaa" is a hard work, it will be nice! |work=Sun |language=Divehi |last=Musthafa |first=Mohamed |date=18 October 2018 |archiveurl=http://archive.fo/HeANc |deadurl=no |archivedate=30 November 2018 |accessdate=30 November 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://mihaaru.com/entertainment/43404 |title="Huvaa" can be viewed through Baiskoafu application |work=Mihaaru |language=Divehi |last=Adhushan |first=Ahmed |date=7 October 2018 |archiveurl=http://archive.fo/1rbt1 |deadurl=no |archivedate=30 November 2018 |accessdate=30 November 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The series and his performance as an irresponsible and lazy husband and a drug addict were positively received.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sun.mv/111524 |title=Nahula's "Huvaa" to be released for streaming tomorrow |work=Sun |language=Divehi |last=Musthafa |first=Mohamed |date=28 November 2018 |archiveurl=http://archive.fo/jEOV8 |deadurl=no |archivedate=30 November 2018 |accessdate=30 November 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://sun.mv/112336 |title=First episode of "Huvaa" was a success |work=Sun |language=Divehi |last=Musthafa |first=Mohamed |date=30 November 2018 |archiveurl=http://archive.fo/dxkFB |deadurl=no |archivedate=30 November 2018 |accessdate=30 November 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
